The study found that when eye movement was minimized (150 msec), schizophrenia patients showed no motion perception deficit, but when eye movement was possible (300 msec), deficits appeared. Additionally, eye tracking benefited control subjects but not patients, and the frequency of eye tracking during speed discrimination was not related to regular eye-tracking performance. This suggests the motion perception deficit is not simply a consequence of eye-tracking abnormality, but rather reflects a specific interaction.  

